I have not tested in 3.1.3 but in 3.1.1 when a login failure is logged in log/audit/atlassian-stash-audit.log via an invalid SSH login attempt no IP is logged.

For an SSH login failure the line in the file is:

{code}
- | AuthenticationFailureEvent | - | 1405951419848 | git | {"authentication-method":"ssh"} | - | -
{code}

However for an invalid login via web interface the IP is logged:

{code}
*ip removed*,127.0.0.1 | AuthenticationFailureEvent | - | 1405942317082 | test | {"authentication-method":"form","error":"The remote authentication server is not available. Please try again later."} | 751x109x0 |
{code}

It would be good if it logged the IP address of the failed attempt so we can use this in fail2ban for example.

I'm writing an internal plugin to enforce that all tags are annotated (among other things).

To do this, I need to call 'git cat-file -t HASH' and look at the result - 'tag' means its an annotated tag and 'commit' means that its an unannotated tag, pointing to a real commit.

GitCommandFactory.type() looks like it would do what I want, however it doesn't work for this case:

type() takes a TypeCommandParamenters object. TypeCommandParameters' path attribute is @Nullable, so its optional, but the actual implementation of the two-arg form of object in DefaultCatFileBuilder treats a null path as an empty string, so the code calls 'git cat-file -t HASH:', which (with the colon) is interpreted by git as looking for the type of the root of the repo, which is always going to be 'directory'.

Trying to use GitCommandBuilderFactory directly (with the one-arg version of 'object') also doesn't work - TypeCatFileOutputHandler uses GitObjectType.fromObjectType to map from the cat-file string return (eg 'commit') to the ContentTreeNode.Type enum. However, while GitObjectType knows about the 'tag' type, the enum only defines the 'tag' key, without a value, so TypeCatFileOutputHander ends up returning null for a tag (and ContentTreeNode.Type.SUBMODULE for a lightweight tag....)

The workaround is to replace calling:

{code}
gitCommandFactory.type(repository, TypeCommandParameters.Builder().changesetId(refChange.getToHash()).build()
{code}

or

{code}
gitCommandBuilderFactory.builder(repository).catFile().type().object(refChange.getToHash()).build(new TypeCatFileOutputHandler()).call()
{code}

with

{code}
gitCommandBuilderFactory.builder(repository).catFile().type().object(refChange.getToHash()).build(new CommandOutputHandler<String>() {
    private final StringOutputHandler outputHandler = new StringOutputHandler();

    @Override
    public void complete() throws ProcessException {
        outputHandler.complete();
    }

    @Override
    public String getOutput() {
        String objectType = StringUtils.chomp(outputHandler.getOutput());

        return objectType;
    }

    @Override
    public void process(InputStream output) throws ProcessException {
        outputHandler.process(output);
    }

    @Override
    public void setWatchdog(Watchdog watchdog) {
        outputHandler.setWatchdog(watchdog);
    }
                    }).call();
{code}

(replacing the String with a proper Enum)

To reproduce, set up a post-receive hook that calls the above and prints out the results, and compare:

{{git tag unannotated; git push --tags}}

and

{{git tag -a -m 'annotated tag' annotated; git push --tags}}

(The comments in GitObjectType are also wrong - 'tag' can only be an annotated, possibly signed, tag, not a lightweight tag, and 'commit' just points to a commit object, which may not be a submodule)

